<TEXT>
colombias crackdown on its cocaine cartels has 
reached as far as the streets of lima where a sudden shortage of 
drug money has sparked wild speculation in dollars 
in the month since colombia declared war on drug traffickers 
visits by colombian narcotics smugglers to perus upper huallaga 
river valley source of most of the worlds coca leaf have dropped 
80 percent according to analysts the illegal trade is believed to 
bring at least 1 billion a year to perus dollarstarved economy 
most of it via the northeastern highland jungles where 60000 
peasant families grow the worlds bestquality coca 
colombian traffickers fly into remote airstrips scattered through 
the region and pay cash dollars for coca paste which they refine 
into cocaine 
the drug dollars then travel in chartered planes and trucks over 
the andes which separate the jungle from the coast and are traded 
for peruvian intis on limas bustling black market 
but the dollars arent flowing as they did 
the number of planes carrying dollars from the jungle has 
dropped from about 15 a week to three said economist alberto 
grana director of the magazine actualidad economica 
some have been quick to try to exploit the dollar shortage 
in a thirdfloor apartment in the ritzy san isidro suburb 
roberto owner of an underground money exchange house is 
juggling two telephones trying to line up a deal for 30000 
with a buyer on one line and a seller on the other hes trying 
to ride the rising exchange rate and take in 150 intis on the dollar 
as his cut three times the margin of a few weeks ago 
the phone never stops here he said 
as he talks people with gym bags and paper sacks stuffed with 
intis shuffle in out of the apartment past a bored guard twirling 
his revolver 
roberto who asked that his full name not be used has five years 
in the business and although the government legalized the black 
market last year he chose not to register to avoid regulations and 
taxes 
theres an incredible diversity in prices right now said 
roberto who stood to make 900 if the deal held 
since aug 19 the unofficial exchange rate at which most dollars 
are sold and bought has shot from 3300 intis to the dollar to 
5300 a 60 percent rise attributed to the scarcity of us currency 
the drug moneys power can be seen in the growth of black market 
trading which has effectively turned perus feeble economy into one 
based on dollars 
carrying pocket calculators and wads of bills eager curbside 
money changers can be seen throughout the capital accosting cars and 
pedestrians to make a deal their numbers have jumped from 300 to 
more than 3000 in just two years 
private exchange houses downtown set the exchange rate according 
to the ebb and flow of available dollars and street traders 
throughout the city are in constant touch by telephone to know the 
latest price 
they said two planes with narcodollars were coming from the 
jungle yesterday but they never appeared so the price went up 
said lucy mejia a 45yearold unemployeed nurse who averages a 
profit of 2 a day as a street corner money changer 
the dollar has become a haven for many whose inti income is eaten 
up by hyperinflation estimated at 5700 percent over the last 12 
months businesses also are desperate for dollars to pay for imports 
even though many of the dollars come from the drug trade it 
doesnt mean that we live off cocaine economist guido pennano 
said recently in a television interview it means that were not 
poorer because of the cocaine 
but because of colombias crackdown on cocaine trafficking 
economists are concerned about perus economy being cut off from one 
of its biggest sources of cash 
the most important impact will be an increase in the inflation 
index said grana explaining that as the dollar rises import 
costs go up 
but political leaders frequently express concern that perus 
economy has been weakened by years of narcodependence 
the narcotraffickers are controlling certain aspects of the 
national economy and at least 25 percent of foreign exchange 
earnings is fed by dollars from the drug traffic said luis 
bedoya a leader in the centerright coalition supporting novelist 
mario vargas llosa for president in next aprils election 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

