<TEXT>
two out of three teachers say they would 
recommend their profession to youngsters but many say they are 
struggling with worsening social ills among students especially 
alcohol abuse a new poll finds 
the annual survey of teacher opinion by the metropolitan life 
insurance co released thursday found the number of teachers in 
grades 712 concerned about student drinking in their schools 
increased from 66 percent in 1985 to 81 percent in the latest survey 
drinking was considered a serious problem by 91 percent of high 
school teachers polled and 87 percent of rural teachers according 
to the survey preparing schools for the 1990s 
in the last five years the proportion of teachers considering 
the dropout problem serious at their schools rose from 40 percent to 
52 percent 
and 70 percent of high school teachers regard drug use as a 
serious problem at their schools up from 58 percent in 1985 
american teachers particularly those in our cities have sent 
an sos about the severity of the outofschool problems facing 
their students albert shanker president of the american 
federation of teachers said in reaction to the poll 
if president bush and the nations governors are serious about 
making education a national priority one of the things they will 
have to do is listen to the messages from the front lines to the 
problems teachers face every day in the classroom shanker said 
and what our teachers are crying out for are solutions to the 
severe problems children face which affect the ability of schools 
to do their job poverty ill health drug abuse and troubled 
families 
the survey appearing less than a week before president bush is 
to convene an education summit with the nations governors was 
conducted by louis harris and associates it was based on a 
telephone survey of a nationally representative sample of 2000 
public school teachers from kindergarten through 12th grade polled 
in may and june the survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 
three percentage points 
on the positive side 81 percent of teachers surveyed said they 
still love to teach twothirds said they would advise a young 
person to enter the teaching profession compared with 45 percent 
five years ago 
fiftythree percent believe education reform has improved their 
schools compared with 43 percent who expressed that view in a 1984 
poll only six percent said school reforms have had a negative 
impact the remainder said the effects were neutral 
but teachers were less enthused about the impact of reform on 
themselves 43 percent said reform has affected teachers positively 
27 percent said they felt neutral and 29 percent said reform has 
had a negative effect on teachers 
eightysix percent said they backed mentorteacher programs in 
which teachers help colleagues improve and 55 percent supported 
career ladder programs which offer teachers the chance to advance to 
the level of master teacher for more pay 
twothirds said they strongly backed creation of schoolbased 
leadership committees of principals teachers and students to 
enforce school rules 
but 64 percent say schools are getting worse at sparing teachers 
administrative busy work 
teachers are most supportive of reform in schools where 
educators are actively involved in making decisions about teaching 
and learning new ideas flourish and student learning improves 
said keith geiger president of the national education association 
the nations largest teacher union 
in places where reform simply means more more graduation 
requirements more hours in the school day more paperwork teachers 
are understandably less enthusiastic he said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

