not be reached are immunization of children before age 2 and flu 
vaccinations for highrisk populations the atlantabased national 
centers for disease control said in its weekly report the report 
referred to a draft of the phs year 2000 objectives for the 
nation 
mcginnis said infant mortality is an area where progress has 
been reasonably good but we need to target areas where the 
population is most vulnerable we have not been able to close the 
gap between blacks and whites and have missed the target for 1990 of 
reducing the rate for blacks 
in a telephone interview mcginnis said that among the tentative 
targets for 2000 were cutting the percentage of adult smokers in 
half to about 15 percent and reducing infant mortality from 104 
per thousand in 1986 to no more than seven per thousand 
other goals he said include raising life expectancy to at least 
78 years from 749 and increasing years of healthy life to 65 years 
from an estimated 60 in 1987 
smoking is a good example said mcginnis a deputy assistant 
secretary for health its accountable for 390000 deaths a year 
its an example of where we can target lowincome and minority 
populations where the most difficult challenges lie 
the 21 areas targeted by the phs for improvement by the year 2000 
include nutrition physical activity and fitness tobacco alcohol 
and other drugs sexual behavior violent and abusive behavior 
vitality and independence of older people environmental health 
occupational safety and health and unintentional injuries 
others are maternal and infant health immunization and 
infectious diseases aids other sexually transmitted diseases 
cholesterol and high blood pressure cancer other chronic 
disorders oral health mental and behavioral disorders health 
education and preventive services and surveillance and data systems 
mcginnis said the planning process was not complete and that 
comment was welcome 
