<TEXT>
the fbi says it wont appeal a federal court 
order that directs changes in promotions and assignments to correct 
what a judge called systematic discrimination against hispanic 
agents 
the bureau made the announcement thursday after solicitor general 
kenneth starr told the fbi he had accepted fbi director william 
sessions recommendation not to appeal the case 
the may 5 order by a federal judge in texas strips fbi 
supervisors of the power to overrule decisions by the bureaus 
career promotion board 
it also set up a panel of three outside attorneys to decide if up 
to 200 hispanic agents should be promoted to make up for past job 
discrimination 
sessions said in a statement that he recommended against 
appealing the order after weighing the myriad legal operational 
and institutional considerations 
we must move beyond the frictions caused by this case to 
address the many vital challenges facing the fbi in the 1990s 
said sessions who added that dropping the appeal was in the best 
interests of fbi employees 
the decision was hailed by rep don edwards dcalif who called 
on the fbi to settle a racial harassment and discrimination lawsuit 
filed by donald rochon a black fbi agent now assigned to the 
philadelphia field office 
rochon claims he and his family were harassed by white agents 
when he worked in chicago and that he suffered retaliation by fbi 
supervisors for pressing his complaints 
thats exactly the right decision something weve been urging 
for many months edwards chairman of the house judiciary 
subcommittee on civil rights said of the fbis decision 
its time for them to move on and get at the root causes of the 
problems said the congressman 
bureau officials refused to comment on the rochon case except to 
cite sessions previous statements that he intended to withhold 
judgment until the facts have been adjudicated 
in the classaction suit joined by 311 of the fbis approximately 
400 hispanic agents us district judge lucius bunton iii of 
midland texas directed the bureau to end its unsystematic 
excessively subjective method of promoting special agents 
bunton said the ability of special agents in charge of field 
offices to overrule promotionboard decisions was anathema to 
nearly every reform advanced by the bureau and ordered by this court 
to improve the fairness and reviewability of the process 
the order followed two years of litigation launched in early 1987 
by bernardo m perez then the no 2 fbi agent in el paso texas 
the suit was filed by perez after a series of demotions from special 
agent in charge of the san juan puerto rico field office to el 
paso which he termed an fbi dumping ground 
bunton ordered perezs promotion and he has since been appointed 
deputy assistant director of the fbis laboratory division in 
washington 
in earlier rulings the judge found that hispanic agents were 
often relegated to what one hispanic agent has described as the 
taco circuit working in hispanic neighborhoods or doing 
language translations 
bunton concluded that hispanic agents were often assigned to such 
undesirable tasks as monitoring spanishspeaking suspects on 
wiretaps 
after he took office in november 1987 sessions reviewed all fbi 
personnel and recruitment policies saying he would tolerate no 
discrimination 
sessions went outside the bureau to hire a new head of the 
reorganized equal employment opportunity office 
bunton acknowledged these steps demonstrate energetic and 
goodfaith effort to correct the disparities found by this court 
but the judge said the fbi had to do more saying the changes 
already implemented while wellintentioned are finetuning of a 
system that requires more dramatic repair 
