<TEXT>
children may be safer from injury at daycare 
centers than at home according to a researcher who suggests that 
more attention to playground hazards could reduce injury rates 
a study of injuries at atlanta daycare centers revealed a lower 
overall death rate for children at daycare centers than children at 
home 
dr jeffrey sacks a medical epidemiologist at the centers for 
disease control in atlanta noted that of the 27 children under 5 
years old who died from injuries in the last 6 months of 1987 none 
were in childcare 
parents have always had the bad news that kids in day care are 
at increased risk of infectious disease sacks said heres some 
good news for a change they are probably at less risk of injury and 
death from injury than they are when theyre not at day care 
sacks and his colleagues studied 143 injuries among 5300 
children at 71 atlanta daycare centers between june 1987 and may 
1988 centers reported any injury that required medical or dental 
attention to the researchers whose study was published in todays 
journal of the american medical association 
the researchers said that 35 percent of children in day care 
could be expected to be injured at the center in a given year they 
extrapolated from their data that if children were to stay at day 
care 24 hours a day 365 days a year 14 percent would incur an 
injury 
a typical injury rate for children in a community in one year 
is about 35 percent sacks said that suggests to us that 
children in child care are probably safer than when they are in the 
community at large 
dr george stern a new orleans pediatrician said although he 
hadnt seen the new study there is a certain amount of logic to 
it 
in a wellsupervised daycare center the environment has been 
looked at for hazards probably more than in the average home said 
stern who edited a daycare manual for the american academy of 
pediatrics 
and many children who are at home do not get the amount of 
ongoing supervision as a child does in a daycare center he said 
in a telephone interview 
in the atlanta study most injuries 58 percent were caused by 
falls and 685 percent were head injuries the study said 54 percent 
of the injuries occurred outside and outside accidents accounted 
for 76 percent of the most serious injuries 
the high number of playground injuries could be cut with a few 
simple measures including the installation of impactabsorbing 
surfaces such as wood chips or sand sacks suggested 
the researchers found that injuries were more likely to occur in 
the summer than the winter on monday and friday than in the middle 
of the week and between the hours of 11 am and noon and 4 pm 
and 5 pm 
they suggested that increased supervision during those periods 
could lower injury rates 
</TEXT>
