<TEXT>
rockwell international corp is suing the 
government claiming conflicting federal rules require it to violate 
hazardous waste disposal laws at the rocky flats nuclear weapons 
plant 
we have taken todays action only because we are caught in the 
middle of an intergovernmental feud for which no satisfactory 
resolution has been found donald r beall rockwell chairman and 
chief executive officer said in a news release issued thursday in 
denver after the suit was filed 
the lawsuit which names the government the justice department 
the department of energy and the environmental protection agency 
asks the court to clarify the obligations of rockwell and the 
government in the operation of the plant 
rockwell operates the plant 16 miles northwest of denver under a 
contract with doe rocky flats produces plutonium triggers for 
nuclear weapons and employs about 6000 workers 
the rockwell lawsuit focuses on plutonium recovery operations 
the application of land disposal restrictions to mixed wastes and 
the handling of recycled water 
doe spokesman ben mccarty based at rocky flats said the agency 
was surprised by the lawsuit but declined to comment further epa 
spokesman nat miullo in denver also declined to comment 
the civil lawsuit filed in us district court in washington 
dc is the latest development in an ongoing series of problems at 
the weapons plant involving disposal of hazardous wastes 
in june federal agents raided the plant as part of an 
investigation into allegations of illegal hazardous waste disposal 
a special federal grand jury is considering evidence in that case 
but has issued no indictments 
federal law prohibits storage of hazardous wastes at a production 
site for more than 90 days but there is no federally approved 
disposal site or treatment process for rocky flats wastes 
rockwell has been stockpiling wastes at rocky flats since idaho 
gov cecil andrus refused to accept further shipments bound for a 
temporary storage dump in idaho earlier this year the government 
plans to open an underground repository near carlsbad nm but 
that has been delayed pending further studies 
on friday rockwell threatened to close the plant unless 
hazardous waste regulations were clarified citing a concern over 
the potential for criminal prosecution later that day doe epa and 
state officials announced a plan to resolve the problems over the 
next year 
but beall said assurances that the company wont face criminal 
prosecution because of the regulation conflicts are insufficient 
considering the investigations already under way 
as an example of the conflicting regulations rockwell cited the 
plutonium residues which are stored at the plant for recycling and 
reuse under doe rules but the lawsuit said the justice department 
and epa claim the residues actually are wastes which are stored 
illegally under epa rules 
