<TEXT>
virginias highest court in the nations 
first appeal of a murder trial based on dna evidence today upheld 
the conviction and death sentence of a man in the rapemurders of 
two women 
the state supreme court in unanimous rulings said dna test 
results submitted as evidence at two of timothy w spencers trials 
were shown to be a reliable scientific technique and the tests 
were properly conducted 
spencer a 26yearold former resident of a richmond halfway 
house was linked to the 1987 rape and murders of susan tucker and 
debbie dudley davis through socalled dna fingerprinting 
dna is the basic genetic material found in human cells everyone 
except identical twins is believed to have a unique dna pattern 
spencer was convicted after samples of semen found at the crime 
scenes in the two cases were compared to dna patterns in spencers 
blood experts testified that the samples matched 
the record is replete with uncontradicted expert testimony 
from scientists about the reliability of dna fingerprinting the 
state court said 
indeed spencer acknowledges that the evidence establishes that 
the dna tests are accepted as reliable within the scientific 
community and that he was unable to find or produce one qualified 
expert to debunk either the theory of dna printing or the statistics 
generated therefrom the court said 
jeffery l everhart an attorney who represented spencer in the 
davis killing argued that the dna procedure which has been in use 
for only a few years is too unproved to be relied upon exclusively 
to put the defendant at the scene of the crime 
spencer also was convicted and sentenced to death in two other 
murders and those cases are still on appeal to the state supreme 
court 
