<TEXT>
editors note sam dimeo a reporter who lives on the island of 
st croix watched as looters stripped stores bare after hurricane 
hugo devastated the island leaving many homeless and hungry here 
is his report 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
hurricane hugo taught 
me two lessons there is little you can do to prepare for the 
devastation of a killer storm and a hurricane can bring out the 
worst in people as easily as it mows down trees and homes 
the first lesson i learned while holed up with my wife and two 
children in a small bathroom for seven hours with only a mattress 
covering the doorway the mattress was sucked in and out by the wind 
like a pumping heart 
the house shook the roof splintered and through it all the wind 
howled it was a lesson of fear fear for the safety of my 
7yearold son my 3yearold daughter and my wife 
i kept thinking of tornados hurricanes spawn tornados 
the tornado never came but when dawn arrived it was a shock to 
see so much devastation including my own house in ruins 
an inspection of the island showed that virtually no telephone or 
power pole was left untouched by hugos wrath i drove my small car 
in and around downed poles trees roofs and assorted pieces of 
roofs 
the real blow came when my neighbor and i drove into the business 
area of town and witnessed the frenzied looting 
these were not mobs or rioters or crazy people out to hurt maim 
and kill they were simply sick people stealing first from hardware 
stores and supermarkets then from any business they could find 
they werent taking basic items for survival 
i saw mothers and fathers looting with their children carrying 
toys plants and plastic halloween pumpkins 
store owners said they were very politely shoved aside by the 
scavengers as they cleaned out stores of such nonessential items as 
bolts of cloth and jewelry 
one store owner said he had a gun to keep the mob away but the 
gun apparently didnt scare anyone they pushed him aside and 
emptied his store even of such items as sports trophies 
in town the stores were systematically looted television and 
radio sets and vcrs were popular items 
one manager of a major department store said his establishment 
and two others nearby survived hugo but not the looters 
a witness saw a woman carrying two full cases of carrot cake mix 
on her head others drove around in trucks loaded with loot 
they seemed so matteroffact about taking what didnt belong to 
them items that would do little to relieve the stress of living 
without electricity and telephones 
an insurance agent told me that people always seem to respond to 
major disasters by looting he said he believed it was a primal 
instinct perhaps he is right 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

