<TEXT>
consumers taking advantage of bargains 
increased their spending in august by 09 percent even though 
incomes rose only 04 percent the government said friday in another 
report pointing toward continued economic expansion 
the commerce department said the jump in consumer spending 
followed a 06 percent gain in july and was the largest since a 11 
percent advance in april 
income growth meanwhile slowed from a 07 percent advance in 
july in large part because of strikes against several major 
telephone companies nevertheless personal incomes have increased 
for nine consecutive months 
consumers are still basically positive in their attitudes 
largely based on a favorable job outlook said david jones an 
economist with aubrey lanston amp co a new york government 
securities dealer 
as long as the job sector holds up and it certainly seems 
likely to do so i think consumers will continue to spend at least 
when theyre given a bargain 
jones pointed to strong rebateinduced sales of automobiles in 
august as an example of consumer bargainbuying and a major element 
of that months consumer spending gain 
in a sense thats good he said as long as consumers buy 
only when given a bargain that will limit the potential for 
inflation 
william k macreynolds forecasting director for the us chamber 
of commerce also attributed the boost in consumer spending in part 
on declining prices and said the report indicates that consumer 
confidence will keep the economy from slipping into a deep 
downturn 
this is a good sign for businesses which have suffered from 
slow growth in consumption and falling profits since last october 
he said 
consumer spending is watched closely as a barometer of economic 
health because it accounts for about twothirds of the nations 
economic activity other recent reports show an economy continuing 
to grow although at a slower pace as the federal reserve continues 
to keep shortterm interest rates high to contain inflation 
personal consumption spending which includes everything except 
interest payments on debt rose 318 billion in august compared 
with a 211 billion advance in july 
purchases of durable goods cars and other bigticket items 
expected to last more than three years rose 229 billion after 
gaining 34 billion in july 
macreynolds said the resurgence in durables spending doesnt 
create new inflationary pressures because prices in that sector have 
risen less than 2 percent in the last year and durables production 
has lagged behind the rest of the economy leaving ample capacity to 
expand 
nondurable goods purchases fell 36 billion after increasing 
48 billion in the previous month 
purchases of services which includes housing costs rose 125 
billion compared with a 13 billion increase in july 
americans disposable or aftertax income rose 04 percent in 
august down slightly from a 07 percent aftertax increase in july 
but their savings rate savings as a percent of disposable income 
fell 67 percent after gaining 17 percent in the previous month 
the key component of the income category wages and salaries 
decreased 92 billion in august compared with a 235 billion 
increase in july payrolls at manufacturing companies rose by 32 
billion up from a july increase of 21 billion 
overall personal consumption spending came in at an annual rate 
of 351 trillion in august after 348 trillion in july 
personal incomes totaled 447 trillion at an annual rate in 
august after a revised 445 trillion in july 
