<TEXT>
some doctors and hospitals illegally deny 
lifesaving treatment to infants born with severe physical and mental 
disabilities said a government report released friday 
decisions to withhold medical treatment food and fluids to these 
disabled children persist in many instances with the tacit 
cooperation of federal state and local government agencies despite 
a federal law prohibiting the practice the study concluded 
the 500page report medical discrimination against children 
with disabilities was released by the us commission on civil 
rights 
the studys conclusions are based on anecdotal evidence an 
examination of how hospital infantcare review committees and child 
protection agencies have enforced the law and a national random 
survey of physician attitudes published late last year 
in that survey 75 percent of the responding physicians said they 
would be neutral or would discourage surgery for infants with spina 
bifida and another severe disability hydrocephalus 
the study concludes that decisions to deny such treatment often 
are not made on the basis of medical judgments and are 
discriminatory 
many times the commission said such decisions are based on 
erroneous judgments concerning the quality of life or social 
judgments that such a persons continued existence places an 
unacceptable burden on families and taxpayers 
this report deals with discrimination not medical judgments 
said commissioner esther buckley 
when medical care is denied to a person with a disability 
because the doctor thinks it is horrible to live a life with a 
disability that is discrimination buckley said at a news 
conference friday 
discrimination on the basis of disability is illegal and in my 
view immoral whether it is practiced by an employer a school a 
hotel a hospital social worker or a doctor making treatment 
decisions echoed commissioner robert a destro 
dr norman fost chairman of the bioethics committee of the 
american academy of pediatrics said the report ignores dramatic 
changes in the treatment of handicapped newborns 
i dont know of a single case of an infant with downs syndrome 
with medical care being withheld in the last three years said 
fost explaining that most instances of treatment denial prior to 
1984 involved infants with downs syndrome or spina bifida 
he charged that the report fails to address the current massive 
problem of overtreatment of these infants as a result of doctors 
fear of legal liability 
its extremist to say that the quality of a patients life is 
irrelevant to medical decisions fost charged the commission 
would have us believe that doesnt matter 
the 4year study was prompted by the 1986 supreme court baby 
doe decision in which the court struck down federal regulations 
that would interfere in parental decisions regarding medical care 
for babies with severe birth defects 
the report criticizes hospitalbased infant care review and 
ethics committees and their monitoring by the department of health 
and human services 
citing a 1987 hhs inspector generals report the study noted 
that the department examined 20 to 36 cases of treatment denial at 
10 hospitals but told child welfare agencies about just three of the 
cases 
the report chided the agenys lack of efforts to estimate from 
the sample studied how many such cases there have been nationwide 
since the courts ruling the commission said that there may be 
hundreds of potential infant doe cases since passage of the 1984 
child abuse amendments 
but the study offered no numbers of documented cases of treatment 
denial since enactment of the legal protections 
destro said most states are not certain which children are 
covered by the law and which arent 
one state utah went so far as to add an entirely new category 
of cases in which treatment could be denied he said 
replying to the report hhs spokeswoman janet hartnett said 
we have conducted a comprehensive statebystate review and 
have concluded that all states which receive funds under the child 
abuse prevention and treatment act are in full compliance with these 
requirements for the protection of disabled infants 
asked if the department agreed with the commissions conclusions 
an official who requested anonymity said there would be no comment 
on the report until a detailed review of it was conducted 
the commission voted in january to approve the final draft of the 
study its release friday followed additional staff work on the 
report to answer questions raised at the time of the vote by members 
of the panel 
commission chairman william b allen was the sole dissenter on 
the eightmember panel 
