<TEXT>
the federal aviation administration on friday 
suspended licenses of the pilot and copilot of a usair jetliner that 
skidded into new yorks east river but the pilots union said the 
crew broke no rules 
faa administrator james b busey cited the crews delay in 
meeting with investigators and in taking drug and alcohol tests 
after the crash that killed two people wednesday night calling 
their actions highly questionable 
the air line pilots association said there was nothing unusual 
in the crews performance no federal rules were broken and the 
crew has cooperated completely with the investigation 
in a statement announcing suspension of the crews pilot 
certificates the faa did not directly blame the pilots for the 
crackup of the 737400 airliner carrying 61 people but said the 
circumstances of the accident are such that the two pilots may no 
longer be qualified to excercise the privileges of an airline 
transport pilot certificate 
national transportation safety board and faa investigators 
interviewed the pilot michael martin and copilot constantine 
kleissaf for the first time on friday the faa said 
the agency had ordered martin and kleissaf to appear at its 
regional headquarters in the jamaica section of new york citys 
queens borough with their pilot certificates logbooks and other 
relevant documents it lifted that order after the two were 
interviewed the faa said 
officials have been trying to determine why the planes 
latenight takeoff for charlotte nc was aborted after it had 
started down the laguardia airport runway 
a pilots suspension may be appealed to safety board 
administrative law judges either the pilot or the faa may appeal 
the judges decision to the fivemember board whose actions are 
binding unless taken by the pilot to us district court the 
suspensions remain in effect while under appeal 
busey said the failure of the pilots to appear in the hours after 
the crash negated the opportunity to get meaningful toxicological 
tests thereby denying us factual information as to whether drugs 
were or were not a factor 
an faa rule requiring postaccident toxicological tests for 
pilots goes into effect later this year 
for these two pilots to have been sequestered for more than 36 
hours after an accident that took two lives and to do so with no 
explanation is highly quesitionable busey said 
the pilots union said that the captain and first officer followed 
standard alpa procedures after the accident and that usair knew the 
pilots whereabouts at all times 
the union in a statement said the cockpit crew would take drug 
tests 
the union criticized the news media for what it said were 
erroneous accounts about the crash 
it said one report that the first officer told rescue workers the 
captain was mumbling and acting irrationally are likely 
based on the fact that the copilot told rescue workers at the 
accident site that he could not hear the captain when he was calling 
out a postaccident shutdown checklist 
union president henry a duffy said reports concerning drug use 
pending homicide investigatons and improper crew communications 
proved to be wrong 
while we understand the new medias need to report events 
duffy said such erroneous reporting does not serve the publics 
need to know hinders the accident investigation process undermines 
the public confidence in the safety of the system and slanders the 
reputation of hte pilots involved 
the union statement included no reaction to the license 
suspensions 
