<TEXT>
motorists can be arrested for leaving an accident 
scene or can lose their license for refusing to undergo drug 
testing but airline pilots are under no such legal obligations 
aviation officials and legal experts said 
the issue of how long flight crew members must stay at an 
accident scene and how soon they must speak with investigators was 
raised by the crash of a usair jetliner into the east river on 
wednesday night 
the pilot michael martin left the scene shortly after his 
boeing 737 skidded off a laguardia airport runway killing two 
passengers and was not interviewed by investigators for more than 
36 hours 
federal officials disagreed on whether his absence hampered the 
crash investigation a spokesman for the federal aviation 
administration said its investigators had been unable to contact the 
pilot and could not say what caused the accident until they learned 
why he aborted the takeoff 
but a spokesman for the national transportation safety board 
which ran the investigation said the absence of the pilot was not 
unusual and had not impeded the probe and that the pilot and 
copilot had agreed thursday to be interviewed on friday afternoon 
its not at all unusual for us not to interview a pilot on the 
same day as the accident said the spokesman ted lopatkiewicz 
pilots also are not required to submit to alcohol and drug 
testing after accidents automobile drivers who refuse to undergo 
such tests face an automatic license suspension in most states 
most states have laws making it a crime for a driver to leave the 
scene of a serious motor vehicle accident but theres no statue 
or regulation that requires a flight crew to stay at the scene or 
even talk with us said michael benson a spokesman for the safety 
board in washington 
crew members almost always make themselves available however 
and the board has the power to subpoena them to appear before its 
investigators those who are interviewed have the right to be 
accompanied by an attorney 
when it takes an ntsb investigations team several hours to reach 
a crash scene as it did in the case of the usair crash the pilot 
and other crew members frequently have left the scene if for no 
other reason than to seek treatment of injuries 
but benson said the situation in new york was complicated by the 
involvement of local police very unusual in an airline crash 
he said who reached the scene soon after the accident and were 
frustrated by the pilots departure 
patricia goldman usairs chief spokeswoman and negligence 
lawyer mark moller a member of the american bar associations 
committee on torts agreed that it was not unusual for pilots to be 
sequestered by their union their airline or their lawyers 
immediately after a crash 
usually the likelihood is hes going to be in pretty bad shape 
after an accident and anything he says can be used against him 
moller said 
airlines have their own rules for flight crew conduct during and 
after accidents goldman would not comment specifically on usairs 
rules except to say that they require a pilot who has not been 
injured to stay at the scene of an accident until the passengers are 
off the plane 
</TEXT>
