<TEXT>
us district judge walter l nixon jr 
imprisoned on a perjury conviction since march 1988 wants the 
senate to let him go from his jail cell back to the federal bench 
it could happen says sen dennis deconcini dariz who sat 
on the impeachment trial committee for former us district judge 
harry claiborne three years ago but even though the impeachment 
proceedings are separate from nixons criminal trial deconcini says 
he doubts the public would understand an acquittal in one following 
conviction in the other 
claiborne also was in prison at the time of his impeachment and 
the lawyer who defended him is less than optimistic about nixons 
chances poor judge nixon doesnt stand a chance says attorney 
oscar goodman blaming the senates decision three years ago to 
begin having a small group of senators conduct impeachment trials 
and then report to the full chamber 
very few of the senators had any comprehension of what the 
proceedings were all about goodman says 
nixon is the 15th person to be impeached by the house and 
scheduled for trial by the senate in the history of the united 
states for the first 197 years of congress that meant trial by the 
full senate 
but when the senate got the claiborne case in 1986 the first 
impeachment in 50 years it appointed a 12member committee to 
preside over the trial and report back to the full body 
after the report from the committee and a secret debate among all 
the members the senate removed claiborne from office nixons trial 
before the senate panel was completed this month and the committee 
is due to report to the full senate in october 
nixons lawyer david stewart has filed a lawsuit in us 
district court claiming the committee method is unconstitutional 
so have the attorneys for us district judge alcee hastings of 
florida who also is awaiting a verdict he was impeached by the 
house and had his trial july 10aug 3 before a senate committee 
chaired by sen jeff bingaman dnm 
deconcini defends the process saying the constitution is silent 
on how the senate is to conduct its trial furthermore he says the 
constitution doesnt give the courts jurisdiction over the senates 
internal procedures 
during the fourday nixon trial that ended sept 13 a committee 
led by sen wyche fowler dga listened with rapt attention 
though seldom with full attendance to the proceedings the trial 
also was broadcast over the closedcircuit congressional cable 
channel 
nixons story is that of an exemplary federal judge whose 
21year career seldom saw a case overturned on appeal but whose 
associations with an eccentric millionaire and a flamboyant county 
prosecutor in hattiesburg miss led him into a tangle of perceived 
illegality adverse local publicity and a federal investigation that 
ended with a perjury conviction 
deconcini who is not on the nixon committee says there is a 
distinction between a criminal conviction and potential removal from 
office which is what the senate does when it convicts on 
impeachment 
they may sound alike and appear alike but they truly are two 
different things he says the constitution does not say that a 
public official must be removed from office following a criminal 
offense 
it is my judgment that we are to make that decision 
deconcini says 
the key figures in the nixon case are 
drew fairchild estranged son of the richest man in hattiesburg 
miss he was arrested on charges of smuggling a ton of marijuana 
into the local airport and released by federal authorities after a 
plea bargain but didnt pay his attorney and later was indicted on 
state charges 
wiley fairchild 72 at the time whose formal education ended 
after the fourth grade but who made a fortune on his ability to 
find oil he complained to nixon that the local prosecutor had his 
son indicted on state charges as a way to blackmail him for the 
legal fees drew owed his attorney 
paul bud holmes a private attorney and nightclub owner 
before he became county prosecutor who admitted he helped have drew 
indicted to help his friend drews attorney collect legal fees 
carroll ingram attorney and second cousin to wiley fairchild 
who helped the elder fairchild with his business dealings and 
arranged a lucrative oil deal between nixon and the oilman 
nixon 56 who was the youngest federal judge in the country 
when he was appointed at age 39 to the bench by president lyndon 
johnson both the defense and prosecution say he was stretched 
financially by the burdens of raising seven children on his judges 
salary 
reid weingarten 36 an attorney with the public integrity 
division of the justice department who had unsuccessfully prosecuted 
judge hastings of florida nixon claims weingarten wanted to get a 
judge 
the house prosecutors say nixon fixed the case against drew 
fairchild because he was grateful for the oil deal he got from wiley 
and wanted more such investments 
nixon says a conversation he had with holmes about the case was 
merely to pass along wiley fairchilds claim that he was being 
blackmailed but that he never discussed the case or said anything 
that influenced its outcome 
holmes backs up the judge on that but gave testimony that casts 
some doubt on whether nixons actions were an effort to ingratiate 
himself with wiley fairchild for more investments 
the articles of impeachment allege 
nixon lied when he told a grand jury he never discussed the case 
against drew fairchild with holmes 
nixon lied when he told a grand jury he had nothing to do 
officially or unofficially with the fairchild case and never 
influenced anyone in the case 
nixon undermined the integrity of the judiciary and 
disobeyed the law by making 14 false or misleading statements during 
an interview with federal investigators and in his sworn grand jury 
testimony 
