<DOCNO> AP890922-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
union carbide corp says it has developed a 
process for making foam seat and furniture cushions that eliminates 
the use of environmentally harmful chlorofluorocarbons 
an international treaty has called for phasing out 
chlorofluorocarbons or cfcs because the gasses damage the 
atmospheric ozone that ozone layer provides protection against the 
suns ultraviolet rays 
the united states has set a goal of eliminating cfcs by the year 
2000 if substitutes are found 
the technology developed by union carbide chemicals and plastics 
co of danbury conn will begin to be made available to 
foamcushion manufacturers before the end of the year with 
widespread use expected within two years company spokesman steven 
gabelman said thursday 
about 10 percent of all cfcs released into the air worldwide come 
from the manufacture of flexible polyurethane foam cushions found in 
bedding seats furniture and various padding according to industry 
figures 
the chemical industry has been scrambling in recent years to 
develop substitutes for cfcs which are used as a blowing agent in 
manufacturing the foam among other uses 
union carbide announced a year ago that it had developed a 
product called ultracel foam which eliminates the need of a blowing 
agent such as cfcs in the manufacture of highgrade flexible foam 
about 20 percent of the market other companies quickly developed a 
similar product 
thursdays annoucement involves a similar process geolite foam 
technology that would be used in manufacturing lowergrade foams 
widely used for quilting fabrics pillows chair cushions 
insulation and packaging that covers the remaining 80 percent of 
the flexible foam industry according to union carbide 
the process as well as use of a special polymer eliminates the 
need to rely on a blowing agent to expand the flexible foam said 
john televantos director of research and development for union 
carbides speciality chemical division 
the environmental protection agency estimates that about 35 
percent of cfcs are used in refrigeration and air conditioning 
areas where industry also has moved toward their gradual 
elimination another 34 percent are used in various plastic foams 
from fast food packaging to cushions 
the new process involves only foams used as flexible cushions 
televantos said the geolite process is expected to be widely 
accepted as a substitute for cfcs because it results in no reduction 
in the quality and firmness needed for seat and furniture cushions 
and costs about the same or less than the process that uses cfcs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

