<TEXT>
as american banks take careful steps to skirt the 
black hole of third world loans they seem to be stumbling blindly 
into another possible multibilliondollar debt trap highrisk junk 
bonds 
three big new york banks set aside extra money this past week to 
cover possible losses on loans to developing nations 
the moves by jp morgan amp co chase manhattan corp and 
manufacturers hanover corp reflected the deepening pessimism about 
the ability of the socalled lessdeveloped countries to repay the 
huge sums lent to them in the 1970s to spur economic growth 
while those bulletbiting measures suggested a more realistic 
view of the third world debt crisis some banking experts worried 
that the same mistakes might be repeated in the junk bond market for 
takeovers and refinancings 
prudentialbache securities inc for example recently issued an 
investor alert about the danger of bank stocks primarily because of 
the increasing involvement of many banks in socalled highly 
leveraged transactions which includes junkbond lending 
this is a large potential problem prudentialbache said 
exposures are meaningful and the loanloss risk is real 
keefe bruyette amp woods a wall street firm that follows the 
banking business said in a study that most big us banks had 
highly leveraged transaction exposure that exceeded 100 percent of 
their equity base many had more exposure in this area than they had 
in third world loans 
still the banks seem to be forging ahead into this new market 
partly because of a fundamental tenet in the banking business they 
get high interest rate margins and can charge big fees 
the trend seemed to accelerate this past week when bankers trust 
co announced plans to become the first bank to manage a corporate 
bond sale under recently relaxed federal rules on the types of 
business that banks can conduct bankers trust will manage a 150 
million issue of junk bonds 
one of the ironies banking analysts see in the bank move into 
junkbond lending is that they were reluctant to get involved in 
this business 10 years ago when it was new and highly profitable 
now they are among the last segments of the financial industry to 
see junk bonds as an opportunity even when there are signs that the 
junkbond market is faltering earlier this month junk prices 
plunged in the worst shakeout ever as retail giant campeau corp 
suffered a financing crisis 
i think part of what banks are doing is an irresistible urge to 
do what others do said james grant editor of grants interest 
rate observer and a frequent critic of the use of corporate debt 
in that theyre not so different from the washington press 
corp and others who do business in groups he said banks are 
following the leaders its a timehonored axiom that banks tend to 
catch on to trends at the tail end 
the insurance added against third world debt losses was 
nonetheless impressive morgan was the most aggressive of the three 
banks adding 2 billion to its reserves the move will result in a 
18 billion loss to the bank for the current financial quarter 
chase boosted its badloan reserves by a third to 29 billion 
and manufacturers hanover boosted its reserves by nearly 1 billion 
to total 24 billion for chase the move will result in a 
thirdquarter loss of 11 billion and manufacturers will take a 
775 million thirdquarter loss 
in other business and economic news this past week 
major airlines raised fares for business travelers and tightened 
cancellation penalties the move instigated by american airlines 
was seen as a way for airlines to absorb the cost of higher fuel 
prices and fall travel bargains offered during the summer 
goverment reports suggested the economy is growing modestly but 
the news did little to help the languishing stock and bond markets 
the labor department said consumer prices steadied in august the 
first time in three years they didnt rise signaling lower 
inflation the commerce department said consumer spending jumped 
sharply in august and the economy grew at a 25 percent rate in the 
second quarter 
